    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Refers to long seats with a back and usually arms; large enough for two or more persons. The terms sofa and settee are virtually interchangeable in 20th-century usage but there is a distinction between the two; a settee is less fully upholstered than a sofa and can even be unupholstered.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000011141/Fleming and Honour, Dictionary of the Decorative Arts (1977)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000046892/Grove Art Online (2003-2008)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Asientos con respaldo y usualmente con brazos; suficientemente largos para una o más personas.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
